 \begin{abstract}
-\noindent As Large Language Models (LLMs) evolve from static chat interfaces into autonomous agents, the computational bottleneck is rapidly shifting from the GPU forward-pass to CPU-bound tool orchestration. Agentic workflows rely heavily on serial, branch-heavy, and I/O-bound tasks---such as JSON parsing, database lookups, and filesystem traversal---which behave more like traditional datacenter Remote Procedure Calls (RPC) than highly parallel machine learning kernels. In this paper, we introduce a decoupled microarchitectural profiling framework utilizing hardware performance counters (PAPI) to isolate and quantify the "Agentic Tax": the systemic overhead imposed by LLM orchestration frameworks. We evaluate compute, memory, and I/O-bound C++ execution kernels, demonstrating that Python-based orchestration and JSON serialization induce latency penalties up to $69.5\times$ compared to native execution[cite: 70, 71]. Furthermore, we apply classical hardware optimizations---including SIMD vectorization (AVX2), software prefetching, and OpenMP concurrency---to the tool kernels. While software prefetching successfully yielded a $14.2\%$ IPC improvement at the kernel level [cite: 215], the end-to-end system speedup remained below $1\%$[cite: 222]. We term this phenomenon the Masking Effect: the execution bloat of the orchestration layer is so massive that it effectively nullifies microarchitectural hardware optimizations[cite: 224]. Ultimately, we argue that the future of agentic AI requires treating the orchestration layer as a high-performance networking data plane.
